  <main>
   <section aria-labelledby="rules" class="card" id="content">
    <h2 class="section-title">Rules & Regulations</h2>
    <div class="rules" id="rulesList">

     <details class="rule"><summary>1. Nothing detrimental to the nationality, independence, sovereignty, multiparty democracy, parliamentary system, or constitutional monarchy of Nepal</summary><p>Nothing detrimental to these principles should be propagated or published during the election period.</p></details>

     <details class="rule"><summary>2. No voting influence based on religion, caste, ethnicity, or language</summary><p>Voters should not be encouraged to vote on these grounds.</p></details>

     <details class="rule"><summary>3. No character assassination</summary><p>No one is entitled to assassinate the character of any candidate or their family member.</p></details>

     <details class="rule"><summary>4. Decent campaign language</summary><p>Candidates must use restrained language that conforms to accepted norms of decency.</p></details>

     <details class="rule"><summary>5. No campaigning 48 hours before election</summary><p>All rallies and campaigns must stop within this period.</p></details>

     <details class="rule"><summary>6. No posters on religious or historic sites</summary><p>These areas must not be used for pasting or painting campaign materials.</p></details>

     <details class="rule"><summary>7. No posters on private residences without consent</summary><p>Consent is mandatory.</p></details>

     <details class="rule"><summary>8. Do not destroy or overwrite others’ posters</summary><p>Snatching, destroying, or damaging another party’s posters is not allowed.</p></details>

     <details class="rule"><summary>9. Remove campaign materials after election</summary><p>Parties must remove posters, pamphlets, and symbols after the election.</p></details>

     <details class="rule"><summary>10. Do not damage election materials</summary><p>No one may amend, damage, or remove official Election Commission materials.</p></details>

     <details class="rule"><summary>11. No publicity using banners or cloth</summary><p>Banner-based publicity is not allowed.</p></details>

     <details class="rule"><summary>12. Allowed poster and pamphlet sizes</summary><p>Pamphlets up to 6" x 10" and posters up to 18" x 22", one color only, with printer details included.</p></details>

     <details class="rule"><summary>13. No plastic material during canvassing</summary><p>Plastic materials are prohibited.</p></details>

     <details class="rule"><summary>14. Vehicle and loudspeaker limits</summary><p>No more than three vehicles and three loudspeakers per candidate.</p></details>

     <details class="rule"><summary>15. Audio use rules</summary><p>Audio devices allowed only 7am–9pm; no prolonged use in one location except public meetings.</p></details>

     <details class="rule"><summary>16. Allowed timing for meetings and rallies</summary><p>Meetings and rallies only allowed between 7am and 9pm; no arms or torch demonstrations.</p></details>

     <details class="rule"><summary>17. Must inform local administration before rallies</summary><p>Political parties must inform concerned authorities before meetings.</p></details>

     <details class="rule"><summary>18. No fear or intimidation</summary><p>Threats, intimidation, force, or temptation must not be used.</p></details>

     <details class="rule"><summary>19. No compelling voters</summary><p>No one should compel voters through threats or religious oaths.</p></details>

     <details class="rule"><summary>20. No writing or painting around polling stations</summary><p>All such materials must be removed before polling.</p></details>

     <details class="rule"><summary>21. No obstructing voters</summary><p>No one may obstruct or attempt to obstruct voters.</p></details>

     <details class="rule"><summary>22. No force or seizure of ballot materials</summary><p>No coercion or seizure of ballot boxes or materials.</p></details>

     <details class="rule"><summary>23. No procession during nomination registration</summary><p>Candidates must not enter restricted areas with a procession.</p></details>

     <details class="rule"><summary>24. No vehicle rallies</summary><p>Truck, tractor, bus, rickshaw, car, or motorcycle rallies are not allowed. Bicycles allowed.</p></details>

     <details class="rule"><summary>25. Only one vehicle on Election Day</summary><p>Each candidate may use only one vehicle.</p></details>

     <details class="rule"><summary>26. No feasts or parties to influence voters</summary><p>Arranging parties or feasts to influence voters is prohibited.</p></details>

     <details class="rule"><summary>27. No slogan chanting during polling or counting</summary><p>No slogans should be chanted during polling and counting.</p></details>

     <details class="rule"><summary>28. Parties must inform workers about code of conduct</summary><p>Parties must ensure supporters understand and follow the rules.</p></details>

     <details class="rule"><summary>29. Candidates must follow all laws and acts</summary><p>This includes all directives and the Election Crimes and Punishment Act of 1990.</p></details>

    </div>

